In Rust, `self` is a special parameter used to reference the current instance of a struct or enum. 

- `self` is used to pass the instance by value, which means the method takes ownership of the instance and can modify it as needed. 
- `&self` is used to pass the instance by shared reference, which means the method can read but not modify the instance. 
- `&mut self` is used to pass the instance by mutable reference, which means the method can both read and modify the instance. 
- `mut self` is used to pass the instance by value, but with the ability to modify it.

Here's an example to illustrate the differences:

```
struct Person {
    name: String,
    age: u8,
}

impl Person {
    fn print_name(self) {
        println!("My name is {}", self.name);
    }

    fn print_age(&self) {
        println!("I am {} years old", self.age);
    }

    fn change_age(&mut self, new_age: u8) {
        self.age = new_age;
    }

    fn change_name(mut self, new_name: String) -> Self {
        self.name = new_name;
        self
    }
}

fn main() {
    let person = Person {
        name: String::from("John"),
        age: 30,
    };

    person.print_name(); // Takes ownership of person and prints "My name is John"

    person.print_age(); // Takes a shared reference to person and prints "I am 30 years old"

    let mut person2 = person;
    person2.change_age(35);
    person2.print_age(); // Takes a mutable reference to person2 and prints "I am 35 years old"

    let person3 = person2.change_name(String::from("Jane"));
    person2.print_name(); // Prints "My name is John" (person2 was not modified)
    person3.print_name(); // Takes ownership of person2 and prints "My name is Jane"
}
```

In this example, `print_name` takes ownership of the `Person` instance and therefore can modify it. `print_age` takes a shared reference to the instance and can only read from it. `change_age` takes a mutable reference to the instance and can modify it. `change_name` takes ownership of the instance, but uses `mut` to allow modifications before returning a new instance with the updated name.

